 in section 5. 4. Be aware of how to use safety equipment and how to perform first aid. 5. Take headcount of students by roll call at the assembly area, report any injured students to the Simulation Coordinator, and organise recreation activities to keep students calm. 6. After the drill, conduct hot debriefs with their students in the classroom. 1. Understand the nature of tsunamis, early warning and evacuation signals, and evacuation procedures. 2. Follow instructions for safe evacuation. 3. Provide feedback during hot debriefs. School maintenance and technical staff 1. Check school buildings regularly and report any structural defects to the School Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Committee. 2. Maintain an inventory of tools and equipment. 3. Post charts showing the locations of equipment required by each Task Team. 4. Advise the School Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Committee about the potentially hazardous and safe areas in the school. 36 Ibid. 37 Ibid. 38 Ministry of Education and Human Resource Development Solomon Islands, Guidelines for Preparing School Disaster Management Plan, 2011. 3. TEAMS AND RESPONSIBILITIES 22 ii. Roles and responsibilities of the School Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Committee and Task Teams39 a) The School Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Committee The School Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Committee is in charge of all tsunami preparedness procedures in the school, including preparedness, drills, and assessments. Chaired by the Headmaster or School Principal, the Committee includes at least seven people representing different stakeholder groups including: \u2022 The school administration (such as the deputy headmaster, teachers, or staff) \u2022 Student representatives (e.g. Scouts, Class Monitors, students with disabilities) \u2022 Parents and community members (e.g. Red Cross) The Committee40: 1. Maintains a list of important telephone numbers and radio contacts (e.g. National Disaster Management Office, Meteorological Department, and Ministry of Education). 2. Leads the development of the school disaster preparedness and evacuation plan that identifies the tsunami risk and resource map for the school, safe assembly area, evacuation routes, and temporary evacuation shelter41. 3. Coordinates the testing of the preparedness plans through organising conduct of tsunami evacuation drills, their evaluation, and incorporating lessons learned to update the school plans at regular intervals (twice per year and after a disaster)42. 4. Plans for how teachers can support their students after they experience a tsunami43. 39 International Finance Corporation, Disaster and Emergency Preparedness: Guidance for Schools, 2010. 40 Ministry of Education and Human Resource Development Solomon Islands, Guidelines for Preparing School Disaster Management Plan, 2011. 41 See section 4 for drafting school preparedness plans. 42 UNDP India, School Disaster Management Plan. 43 See section 7 on Supporting Students After a Tsunami for further information. The School Emergency & Disaster Preparedness Committee The Early Warning Team The Drill Operations Task Teams The Logistics Team The Administration & Finance Team The Documentation Team The Simulation Coordinator Evacuation Assistants The First Aid and Relief Team The Rescue Team The Safety & Security Team Figure 2: Proposed Structure of Preparedness Committee and Task Teams Adapted from: International Finance Corporation, Disaster and Emergency Preparedness: Guidance for Schools, 2010. 23 b) The Early Warning Team The Early Warning Team consists of at least three members from the school administration staff. c) The Simulation Coordinator The Simulation Coordinator is a senior representative of the school, most likely the Headmaster or School Principal or Deputy Headmaster. S/he leads the School Emergency and Disaster Preparedness Committee in conducting the evacuation.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}